06816nam a22009495i 9780814759851DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147598517 a10.18574/nyu/9780814757420.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)548482  a(OCoLC)779828210  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ792.U5 C424 2009 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a305.2309730903300aChildren and Youth in a New Nation /ced. by James Marten. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource :b10 black and white illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChildren and Youth in America ;v200tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. No Greater Distinction -- t1. Boy Soldiers of the American Revolution -- t2. Martha Jefferson and the American Revolution in Virginia -- t3. In Franklin’s Footsteps -- tPart II. Finding a Place to Belong -- t4. French and American Childhoods -- t5. Growing up on the Middle Ground -- t6. A Child Shall Lead Them -- tPart III. Taking a Flying Leap -- t7. “A Few Thoughts in Vindication of Female Eloquence” -- t8. “Pictures of the Vicious ultimately overcome by misery and shame” -- tPart IV. A Hard World -- t9. Children of the Public -- t10. Schooling and Child Health in Antebellum New England -- tPart V. Documents -- t11. A Teenager Goes Visiting -- t12. “Though the Means Were Scanty” -- t13. A Stolen Life Excerpts from the Narrative of William W. Brown, a Fugitive Slave, Written by Himself (1847) -- tQuestions for Consideration -- tSuggested Readings -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the early years of the Republic, as Americans tried to determine what it meant to be an American, they also wondered what it meant to be an American child. A defensive, even fearful, approach to childhood gave way to a more optimistic campaign to integrate young Americans into the Republican experiment.In Children and Youth in a New Nation, historians unearth the experiences of and attitudes about children and youth during the decades following the American Revolution. Beginning with the revolution itself, the contributors explore a broad range of topics, from the ways in which American children and youth participated in and learned from the revolt and its aftermaths, to developing notions of “ideal” childhoods as they were imagined by new religious denominations and competing ethnic groups, to the struggle by educators over how the society that came out of the Revolution could best be served by its educational systems. The volume concludes by foreshadowing future “child-saving” efforts by reformers committed to constructing adequate systems of public health and child welfare institutions.Rooted in the historical literature and primary sources, Children and Youth in a New Nation is a key resource in our understanding of origins of modern ideas about children and youth and the conflation of national purpose and ideas related to child development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChild welfarexHistoryxUnited States. 0aChild welfarezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChildrenxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxHistory. 0aChildrenxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aChildrenzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aYouthxHistoryx18th centuryxUnited States. 0aYouthxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aYouthzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aYouthzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Gretchen A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo